      "content": "Released on March 23, 2009 via Relapse Records, Obscura's \"Cosmogenesis\" arrived as one of the most ambitious technical death metal records of its era — a landmark album that pushed the boundaries of what extreme metal composition could achieve. Drummer Hannes Grossmann's performance on the record stands as a defining moment in modern progressive death metal: an articulate, mechanically precise, and musically expressive display that established him as one of the genre's most important practitioners.\n\nThe album was tracked at V. Santura's Woodshed Studios in Germany — the producer (also of Triptykon and Dark Fortress) bringing the engineering vision that would shape Obscura's signature sound. V. Santura's understanding of how to capture extreme metal drumming with both clarity and weight made Woodshed the ideal environment for Grossmann's nuanced playing. Every double-bass roll, every blast beat, every odd-time tom fill on Cosmogenesis sits in the mix with the kind of definition that became Obscura's sonic signature across the rest of their catalog.\n\nHannes Grossmann's approach to \"Cosmogenesis\" combined the death metal velocity vocabulary he had developed in his earlier Necrophagist work with the compositional sophistication that Obscura's progressive material demanded. Songs like \"Anticosmic Overload,\" \"Choir of Spirits,\" and the title track \"Cosmogenesis\" require sustained double-kick passages running underneath fretless bass solos, polyrhythmic blast sections that align with seven-string guitar tapping figures, and dynamic transitions where the kit must shift from full-intensity blasts to atmospheric ride patterns within bars. Grossmann executes this material with a clarity that turned every individual stroke into musical information.\n\nHis setup on the record — a high-end production shell pack, Meinl Byzance cymbals (Grossmann is a long-standing Meinl artist), double 22\" bass drums with high-speed pedals, and Vic Firth signature-grade sticks — was built for both studio precision and the touring demands that would follow the album's release. This article breaks down every component of that setup and explains how each one contributed to the iconic Cosmogenesis drum sound.\n\nBeyond the gear itself, Grossmann's performance on Cosmogenesis is now studied as a template for the modern progressive death metal drummer. The album proved that technical death metal could be melodic, musically composed, and emotionally evocative without sacrificing any of the genre's traditional intensity. For drummers working in extreme metal today, Cosmogenesis remains essential listening — and the gear behind it remains essential reference.",
