      "description": "Hannes Grossmann's Meinl Byzance setup is one of the most distinctive cymbal signatures in modern extreme metal — and \"Cosmogenesis\" is one of the recordings where that signature is most clearly captured. Grossmann is a long-standing Meinl artist, and the Byzance series (Meinl's hand-hammered, dark-character professional line) provided the tonal palette that defines Obscura's drum sound across the band's entire catalog.\n\nThe Byzance series produces darker, more complex cymbal tones than mainstream bright-alloy options — a character that suited Cosmogenesis perfectly. Obscura's seven-string guitar work creates a thick upper-midrange environment, and the Byzance cymbals breathe within that environment rather than competing with it. The 14\" Medium hi-hats anchor Grossmann's rhythmic pulse with a darker, more musical voice than typical metal hi-hat choices, allowing rapid 16th-note patterns to speak clearly without sounding harsh.\n\nThe 17\" and 19\" Byzance Medium crashes form the accent palette across Cosmogenesis. Their controlled decay and complex tonal content suit V. Santura's natural-drum production aesthetic — these are cymbals that record well without aggressive EQ correction or compression. On tracks like \"Anticosmic Overload\" and \"Cosmogenesis\" itself, each crash arrives as a deliberate musical event, not a reflexive accent.\n\nThe 22\" Medium ride is the cornerstone of Grossmann's atmospheric playing on the record. Obscura's compositions include sustained ride passages — particularly the bass solo sections featuring Jeroen Paul Thesseling's fretless playing — where the ride cymbal must provide texture and shimmer beneath melodic instrumental statements. The Byzance ride's dark complexity gives these passages their distinctive atmospheric quality.\n\nThe 18\" China and 10\" Splash round out the effects vocabulary. The China appears at the album's most aggressive blast peaks; the Splash provides quick polyrhythmic accents that align with Christian Münzner's guitar tapping figures. Together, these effects cymbals give Grossmann the full tonal range Cosmogenesis demands.",
