      "content": "Released on August 10, 2004 via Relapse Records, Necrophagist's \"Epitaph\" stands as one of the foundational technical death metal albums — a record that established the modern tech-death template and launched Hannes Grossmann's career as one of extreme metal's most respected drummers. Grossmann's performance on the album, particularly on tracks like \"Stabwound,\" \"Ignominious & Pale,\" and \"Seven,\" became reference material for the entire next generation of technical death metal drumming.\n\nThe album was a long-awaited follow-up to Necrophagist's 1999 debut \"Onset of Putrefaction\" (which had been recorded almost entirely by founder Muhammed Suiçmez). Epitaph was the first Necrophagist record with a proper full-band lineup, and Grossmann's arrival as the drummer transformed the band's sonic possibilities. Where Onset of Putrefaction had used programmed drumming with intricate but mechanical results, Epitaph captured a human drummer at the absolute peak of technical capability — and the difference was decisive for the album's impact on the genre.\n\nHannes Grossmann's approach to Epitaph combined the dense vocabulary required by Suiçmez's neoclassical guitar compositions with the sustained extreme metal velocity that the songs demanded. Every track features sustained double-bass at sixteenth-note tempos, blast beat passages aligned to complex guitar phrasing, and polyrhythmic fills that move between snare, toms, and bass drums with surgical precision. The album's most famous track, \"Stabwound,\" opens with a drum vocabulary so dense it became a benchmark for technical death metal drumming — every fill on the track is now studied by extreme metal drummers as a foundational text.\n\nHis setup on the record — Tama Starclassic Performer (or comparable high-end production shells), Meinl cymbals (including early Pure Alloy and developing Byzance configurations), high-speed double pedals, and Vic Firth sticks — was built for the studio precision that Suiçmez's production demanded. Necrophagist produced the album themselves, and the engineering approach prioritized articulation above all else: every individual stroke needed to register as a discrete event, even at the album's most intense passages.\n\nFor drummers studying extreme metal, Epitaph remains essential listening more than two decades after its release. The album is one of the most documented Necrophagist records — partially because it was the band's most successful release, and partially because of the magnitude of Grossmann's contribution. This article breaks down the gear behind that performance.",
