      "description": "Hannes Grossmann's drum kit on \"Epitaph\" represented the high-end production shell pack required for studio-grade technical death metal recording in 2004 — a Tama Starclassic Performer or comparable Pearl Reference shell pack chosen for the combination of attack and articulation that Necrophagist's material demanded. Epitaph asks the kit to perform an unusual concentration of high-velocity work: sustained double-bass passages, blast beat sections, and polyrhythmic fill vocabulary all occurring within single tracks at tempos where every stroke must register cleanly.\n\nThe double 22\" x 18\" bass drum configuration is fundamental to the album's rhythmic identity. Tracks like \"Stabwound,\" \"Ignominious & Pale,\" and \"Seven\" sustain 16th-note double-bass at velocities where each individual stroke needs to occupy its own clear sonic territory. The 22\" diameter delivers the low-frequency body the music requires, while the 18\" depth provides the punchy attack character that Suiçmez's self-production prioritized.\n\nGrossmann's tom configuration is compact and efficient: 10\" and 12\" rack toms paired with 14\" and 16\" floor toms. This four-tom spread covers the pitch range his fill vocabulary requires while remaining tight enough for the rapid articulation Necrophagist's music demands. Tom fills on Epitaph are dense — often involving cross-tom rolls and polyrhythmic patterns at high velocity — and the compact spread keeps these phrases physically reachable without compromising speed.\n\nThe shell construction matters significantly in Epitaph's production context. Necrophagist's self-production approach captured the acoustic kit's natural voice with relatively traditional studio techniques, and the high-end shell pack delivered the articulation and projection required to make that approach succeed.",
