      "description": "Hannes Grossmann's snare drum on Epitaph needed to perform across the full vocabulary of high-velocity tech-death drumming: rapid ghost-note patterns, polyrhythmic snare placement against bass drum figures, full-velocity rim-shot accents during blast sections, and sustained groove punctuation through Necrophagist's most complex guitar arrangements. A 14\" x 6.5\" professional snare drum provided the dimensional balance for this range — enough depth for tonal body, tight enough at the heads for rapid articulation.\n\nThe tuning approach on Epitaph emphasized clarity through Necrophagist's dense guitar layering. Muhammed Suiçmez's seven-string and six-string compositions create thick midrange environments, and the snare must cut through without losing tonal identity. Grossmann's snare voice on the album balances brightness and body, registering with consistent character whether played at ghost-note dynamics or full-velocity rim-shot intensity.\n\nOn \"Stabwound\" specifically — one of the most studied drum tracks in modern extreme metal — the snare appears in nearly every conceivable rhythmic position: backbeats, offbeats, polyrhythmic accents, ghost-note flurries, and blast beat strokes. Each of these positions has consistent tonal character across the track, evidence of disciplined tuning and the snare drum's capacity to perform across that dynamic range.\n\nFor drummers studying the album, Grossmann's snare playing on Epitaph is one of its most instructive elements — proof that tech-death snare work benefits from professional drums tuned for musical clarity rather than maximum aggression alone.",
