      "description": "Hannes Grossmann's Meinl cymbal setup on Epitaph captured an earlier stage of the signature voice that would fully mature on Obscura's Cosmogenesis five years later. Grossmann is a long-standing Meinl artist, and Epitaph documents the cymbal configuration he was using as his Meinl partnership was developing toward its mature form. The setup combined early Pure Alloy elements with developing Byzance configurations — a transitional period in his cymbal voice that produced the distinctive Epitaph cymbal palette.\n\nThe 14\" Medium hi-hats anchor the album's rhythmic pulse. At Necrophagist's tempos — frequently approaching or exceeding 220 BPM — the hi-hats must articulate rapidly without losing tonal character. Grossmann's choice of medium-weight Meinl hi-hats produces the cutting attack and articulation his playing demands while remaining musical enough to blend with the dense guitar arrangements.\n\nThe 17\" and 19\" Medium crashes provide the accent palette across the album. Tech-death music is accent-dense — crashes occur at structural transitions, riff changes, and rhythmic emphasis points throughout every track — and the two-crash configuration gives Grossmann tonal contrast for these accents. The 17\" delivers fast, focused crashes for rapid transitions; the 19\" provides fuller, more sustained crashes for larger structural moments.\n\nThe 22\" Medium ride sees significant use across Epitaph in the album's more groove-oriented passages. While Epitaph is primarily a blast-and-double-bass album, sections of \"Ignominious & Pale\" and \"Seven\" feature ride work that creates textural contrast against the more aggressive sections.\n\nThe 18\" China appears at the album's most aggressive intensity peaks. Its trashy, explosive character provides the aggressive accent voice that tech-death's climactic moments demand.",
