      "title": "Capturing Epitaph: Necrophagist Self-Production",
      "content": "\"Epitaph\" was self-produced by Necrophagist at studios in Germany, with Muhammed Suiçmez taking the central production role. This self-production approach gave the band complete control over the sonic identity of the album — every engineering choice reflected the band's vision for what tech-death drum recording should sound like.\n\n**Microphone Approach:**\nThe Epitaph drum sound used relatively traditional close-miking techniques: dynamic mics on each kick drum, top and bottom snare microphones, individual mics on each tom (likely Sennheiser MD421-class dynamics), pencil condensers on hi-hat and ride, and a stereo overhead pair. Room ambience was used sparingly — Epitaph is a closer, more focused drum sound than the more atmospheric approach Obscura would take on Cosmogenesis five years later.\n\n**Triggering and Sample Replacement:**\nThe album incorporates some bass drum reinforcement to ensure each individual stroke registers cleanly at high velocity — a common practice in 2004-era tech death production. The triggering on Epitaph is disciplined: kicks register with consistent attack character throughout the album without overwhelming the natural drum tone.\n\n**Mix Approach:**\nThe drum mix on Epitaph emphasizes articulation above all else. Suiçmez's production prioritized clarity at the album's most dense passages — when \"Stabwound\" or \"Ignominious & Pale\" reach their highest-velocity sections, every stroke remains discernible. This is the production discipline that made Epitaph an instructional reference for tech-death drumming.\n\n**The Result:**\nEpitaph's drum sound became one of the reference templates for technical death metal production. Many of the subsequent tech-death albums of the mid-to-late 2000s cited Epitaph as a sonic benchmark, and Grossmann's performance on the record established him as one of the genre's defining drummers.",
